A design pattern is a proven, reusable solution to a recurring problem in software design. It's not code itself but a conceptual template.
In Python, Patterns adapt to Python's dynamic and flexible nature, often requirigin less boilerplate compared to languagues like java or C++.

Why it is used: 
    Consistency -> Provide a common vocabulary among developers.
    Efficiency -> Save time by reusing established solutions instead of reinventing the wheel.
    Maintainability -> Make systems easier to extend and refactor.
    Scalability -> Help manage complexity in large projects.
    Best Practice -> Encourage clean architecture and separation of concerns.

Intent:
    Object Creation Issues -> Avoid tight coupling when instantiating classes(e.g. Factory, Singleton)
    Structural Complexity -> Organize relationships between classes and objects(e.g. Adapter, Composite).
    Behavioral Challenges -> Manage communication and responsibility between objects(e.g. Observer, Strategy)

Where it is used:
    Enterprise Application -> Large-scale systems requiring modularity and scalability.
    Frameworks & Libraries -> Django, Flask, and other Python frameworks internally use patterns.
    Game Development -> For managing states, events, and object lifecycles.
    Data Science & ML Piplines -> Strategy patterns for model selection, Observer for event-driven updates.
    Local Projects -> Even small shop management systems benefit from patterns like Singleton(for database connections) or
                      Observer(for notifications)
                
Design Patterns are grouped into three main categories:
  1. Creational (Object creation mechanisms)
     i. Singleton
     ii. Factory
     iii. Builder
     iv. Prototype
  2. Structural (Composition and orignization of classes/objects)
     i. Adapter
     ii. Decorator
     iii. Composite
     iv. Proxy
  3. Behavioral(Communcation and responsibility between objects)
     i. Observer
     ii. Strategy
     iii. Command
     iv. State

Essentail Principles Behind Design Patterns:
    1. DRY(Don't Repeat Yourself)
       -> Avoid duplicate logic
    2. KISS(Keep It Simple, Stupid)
       -> Avoid unnessary complexity
    3. SOLID Principles
        S -> Single Responsibility Principle(one class -> one job)
        O -> Open/Closed Principle(Open for extension, closed fro modification)
        L -> Liskov Substitution Principle(Child class should replace parent safely)
        I -> Interface Segregation(many small interfaces -> one big interface)
        D -> Dependency Inversion(Depend on abstractions, not concrete classes)

Key Components of Any Design Pattern
1. Intent -> What problem it solves.
2. Stucture -> How classes/objects are arranged.
3. Participants -> Classes/objects involved.
4. Collaboration -> How they interact
5. Consequences -> Pros and Cons
    